/*
Problem: 33. Search in Rotated Sorted Array

Approach:
1. At every step, one half of the array is always sorted.
2. Identify whether the left half or the right half is sorted.
3. Check if the target lies inside the sorted half.
4. If yes, search in that half; otherwise, search in the other half.

Time Complexity: O(log n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {

        int n = nums.size();
        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;

        while (st <= end) {

            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target)
                return mid;

            // Left half is sorted
            if (nums[mid] >= nums[st]) {

                if (target >= nums[st] && target < nums[mid]) {
                    end = mid - 1;
                } else {
                    st = mid + 1;
                }
            }

            // Right half is sorted
            else {

                if (target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[end]) {
                    st = mid + 1;
                } else {
                    end = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};

/*
==========================================
My Misconceptions / Learnings
==========================================

1. ❌ Wrong Mid Calculation

Initially I wrote:

    mid = st + ((st - end) / 2);

Correct:

    mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

Reason:
Using (st - end) may produce a negative value, leading to an incorrect
middle index.

------------------------------------------

2. ❌ Checking if Left Half is Sorted

Initially:

    nums[mid] > nums[st]

Correct:

    nums[mid] >= nums[st]

Reason:

When st == mid, the left half contains only one element, which is
still considered sorted.

Example:

nums = {3,1}

Initially:

st = 0
mid = 0

nums[mid] == nums[st]

Using '>' incorrectly assumes the right half is sorted.

------------------------------------------

3. ❌ Incorrect Range Check for Left Half

Initially:

    nums[mid] > target && nums[st] <= target

Although this works logically, it is clearer and follows the standard
binary search pattern to write:

    target >= nums[st] && target < nums[mid]

Reason:

We are checking whether the target belongs to the sorted interval:

[ nums[st] ... nums[mid] )

Left boundary is included because the target may be at st.

Mid is excluded because we already checked:

    if(nums[mid] == target)

------------------------------------------

4. ❌ Incorrect Thinking About the Right Half

The correct range is:

( nums[mid] ... nums[end] ]

Therefore the condition becomes:

    target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[end]

Reason:

Mid is already checked.

End can still be the answer.

------------------------------------------

5. ✅ Important Observation

In every iteration (without duplicates),

either

Left Half

or

Right Half

is guaranteed to be sorted.

The entire algorithm depends on identifying the sorted half first.

------------------------------------------

6. ✅ Key Conditions to Remember

Left Half Sorted

    nums[mid] >= nums[st]

Target inside Left Half

    target >= nums[st] && target < nums[mid]

Right Half Sorted

    nums[mid] < nums[st]

Target inside Right Half

    target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[end]

------------------------------------------

7. ✅ Why Exclude 'mid' in the Range Check?

Because the very first condition is:

    if(nums[mid] == target)
        return mid;

So there is no need to include mid again while deciding which half
to search.

------------------------------------------

Possible Optimization:

The solution is already optimal.

Time Complexity : O(log n)
Space Complexity : O(1)
